        icon: '🔢',
        lessonNotes: `<h4>Number Bases and Numeration Systems</h4>
<p>A <strong>number base</strong> (or radix) tells you how many unique digits are used in a counting system. Understanding number bases is essential for WASSCE Mathematics and forms the foundation of modern computing and digital electronics.</p>

<h4>The Four Main Number Bases</h4>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Base 10 (Decimal):</strong> Uses digits 0 to 9. This is the everyday counting system. Place values are powers of 10: ones, tens, hundreds, thousands, and so on.</li>
  <li><strong>Base 2 (Binary):</strong> Uses only digits 0 and 1. This is the language of computers. Place values are powers of 2: 1, 2, 4, 8, 16, 32, 64, 128 from right to left.</li>
  <li><strong>Base 8 (Octal):</strong> Uses digits 0 to 7. Place values are powers of 8: 1, 8, 64, 512 from right to left.</li>
  <li><strong>Base 16 (Hexadecimal):</strong> Uses digits 0 to 9 and letters A to F, where A=10, B=11, C=12, D=13, E=14, F=15. Place values are powers of 16.</li>
</ul>

<h4>Converting Decimal to Binary (Repeated Division by 2)</h4>
<p>To convert a decimal number to binary, divide the number repeatedly by 2 and record the remainders. Read the remainders from bottom to top.</p>
<p><strong>Example:</strong> Convert 45 to binary.</p>
<ul>
  <li>45 divided by 2 = 22 remainder <strong>1</strong></li>
  <li>22 divided by 2 = 11 remainder <strong>0</strong></li>
  <li>11 divided by 2 = 5 remainder <strong>1</strong></li>
  <li>5 divided by 2 = 2 remainder <strong>1</strong></li>
  <li>2 divided by 2 = 1 remainder <strong>0</strong></li>
  <li>1 divided by 2 = 0 remainder <strong>1</strong></li>
</ul>
<p>Reading remainders from bottom to top: 45 in decimal = <strong>101101</strong> in binary. Always write the answer with the subscript base notation: 101101<sub>2</sub>.</p>

<h4>Converting Binary to Decimal (Place Values Method)</h4>
<p>Write out the binary place values from right to left: 1, 2, 4, 8, 16, 32, 64, 128. Multiply each binary digit by its place value and add the results.</p>
<p><strong>Example:</strong> Convert 101101<sub>2</sub> to decimal.</p>
<ul>
  <li>1 x 32 = 32</li>
  <li>0 x 16 = 0</li>
  <li>1 x 8 = 8</li>
  <li>1 x 4 = 4</li>
  <li>0 x 2 = 0</li>
  <li>1 x 1 = 1</li>
  <li>Total = 32 + 0 + 8 + 4 + 0 + 1 = <strong>45</strong></li>
</ul>

<h4>Converting Decimal to Octal (Repeated Division by 8)</h4>
<p>Use the same repeated division method, but divide by 8 instead of 2.</p>
<p><strong>Example:</strong> Convert 156 to octal. 156 divided by 8 = 19 remainder 4. 19 divided by 8 = 2 remainder 3. 2 divided by 8 = 0 remainder 2. Reading bottom to top: 156<sub>10</sub> = <strong>234</strong><sub>8</sub>.</p>

<h4>Binary to Hexadecimal Shortcut</h4>
<p>Group the binary digits into sets of <strong>four</strong> from the right. Convert each group of four binary digits into a single hexadecimal digit. This shortcut works because 2<sup>4</sup> = 16.</p>
<p><strong>Example:</strong> Convert 10111101<sub>2</sub> to hexadecimal. Group into fours: 1011 and 1101. Convert 1011: 8+2+1 = 11 = B. Convert 1101: 8+4+1 = 13 = D. Answer: <strong>BD</strong><sub>16</sub>.</p>

<h4>Binary to Octal Shortcut</h4>
<p>Group the binary digits into sets of <strong>three</strong> from the right. Convert each group to its octal equivalent. This works because 2<sup>3</sup> = 8.</p>
<p><strong>Example:</strong> Convert 101110<sub>2</sub> to octal. Group into threes: 101 and 110. Convert 101 = 4+1 = 5. Convert 110 = 4+2 = 6. Answer: <strong>56</strong><sub>8</sub>.</p>

<h4>Addition in Binary</h4>
<p>Binary addition follows four basic rules:</p>
<ul>
  <li><strong>0 + 0 = 0</strong></li>
  <li><strong>0 + 1 = 1</strong></li>
  <li><strong>1 + 0 = 1</strong></li>
  <li><strong>1 + 1 = 10</strong> (write 0, carry 1)</li>
  <li><strong>1 + 1 + 1 = 11</strong> (write 1, carry 1)</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Example:</strong> Add 1011<sub>2</sub> + 1101<sub>2</sub>. Starting from the right: 1+1=10 (write 0, carry 1), 1+0+1=10 (write 0, carry 1), 0+1+1=10 (write 0, carry 1), 1+1+1=11 (write 11). Result: <strong>11000</strong><sub>2</sub>. Verify: 11+13=24, and 11000<sub>2</sub> = 16+8 = 24. Correct.</p>

<h4>Subtraction in Binary</h4>
<p>Binary subtraction rules include borrowing. When you subtract 1 from 0, borrow from the next column: <strong>10 - 1 = 1</strong>.</p>
<p><strong>Example:</strong> Subtract 0101<sub>2</sub> from 1101<sub>2</sub>. 1-1=0, 0-0=0, 1-1=0, 1-0=1. Result: <strong>1000</strong><sub>2</sub>. Verify: 13-5=8, and 1000<sub>2</sub> = 8. Correct.</p>

<h4>Common WASSCE Mistakes to Avoid</h4>
<ul>
  <li>Forgetting to carry in binary addition when 1+1 occurs. Always write 0 and carry 1 to the next column.</li>
  <li>Reading the remainders in the wrong direction during repeated division. Always read from the <strong>last remainder to the first</strong>.</li>
  <li>Confusing the grouping size: use groups of <strong>3</strong> for octal and groups of <strong>4</strong> for hexadecimal conversion from binary.</li>
  <li>Not adding a leading zero when grouping binary digits if the leftmost group has fewer than the required digits.</li>
  <li>Forgetting to write the base subscript in your final answer, which can cost marks in WASSCE.</li>
</ul>

<h4>WASSCE-Style Practice Questions</h4>
<ul>
  <li>Convert 110101<sub>2</sub> to base 10.</li>
  <li>Convert 89<sub>10</sub> to binary.</li>
  <li>Add 10110<sub>2</sub> + 11011<sub>2</sub> and express the result in base 10 to verify.</li>
  <li>Convert 3A7<sub>16</sub> to decimal.</li>
  <li>Convert 256<sub>8</sub> to binary using the shortcut method.</li>
</ul>`,
