        name: 'Fractions, Decimals & Percentages',
        icon: '½',
        lessonNotes: `<h4>Fractions, Decimals and Percentages</h4>
<p>Fractions, decimals and percentages are three different ways of expressing parts of a whole. Mastering their interconversion and operations is critical for WASSCE Mathematics, as they appear in both pure calculation questions and real-world word problems.</p>

<h4>Types of Fractions</h4>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Proper fraction:</strong> The numerator is smaller than the denominator. Example: 3/7. The value is less than 1.</li>
  <li><strong>Improper fraction:</strong> The numerator is greater than or equal to the denominator. Example: 9/4. The value is greater than or equal to 1.</li>
  <li><strong>Mixed number:</strong> A whole number combined with a proper fraction. Example: 2 and 1/4. Convert to improper fraction for calculations: multiply the whole number by the denominator and add the numerator, keeping the same denominator. 2 and 1/4 becomes (8+1)/4 = 9/4.</li>
  <li><strong>Equivalent fractions:</strong> Fractions with the same value but different numerators and denominators. Example: 1/2 = 2/4 = 3/6.</li>
</ul>

<h4>Operations with Fractions</h4>
<p><strong>Addition and Subtraction:</strong> You must find a <strong>common denominator</strong> before adding or subtracting. The Lowest Common Denominator (LCD) is the smallest number that both denominators divide into evenly.</p>
<ul>
  <li>Example: 2/3 + 3/4. LCD of 3 and 4 is 12. Convert: 8/12 + 9/12 = 17/12 = 1 and 5/12.</li>
  <li>Example: 5/6 - 1/4. LCD is 12. Convert: 10/12 - 3/12 = 7/12.</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Multiplication:</strong> Multiply <strong>straight across</strong>. Multiply numerator by numerator and denominator by denominator. Simplify by cancelling common factors before multiplying where possible.</p>
<ul>
  <li>Example: 3/5 x 10/9. Cancel: 3 and 9 share factor 3; 10 and 5 share factor 5. This gives 1/1 x 2/3 = 2/3.</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Division:</strong> Multiply the first fraction by the <strong>reciprocal</strong> (flip) of the second fraction. Change the division sign to multiplication and invert the second fraction.</p>
<ul>
  <li>Example: 4/7 divided by 8/21. Becomes 4/7 x 21/8. Cancel: 4 and 8 share factor 4; 21 and 7 share factor 7. Gives 1/1 x 3/2 = 3/2 = 1 and 1/2.</li>
</ul>

<h4>Converting Between Fractions, Decimals and Percentages</h4>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Fraction to decimal:</strong> Divide the numerator by the denominator. 3/4 = 3 divided by 4 = 0.75.</li>
  <li><strong>Decimal to fraction:</strong> Write the decimal as a fraction with a power of 10 as denominator, then simplify. 0.35 = 35/100 = 7/20.</li>
  <li><strong>Fraction to percentage:</strong> Convert to decimal first, then multiply by 100. Or multiply the fraction by 100. 3/5 x 100 = 60%.</li>
  <li><strong>Percentage to fraction:</strong> Write the percentage over 100 and simplify. 45% = 45/100 = 9/20.</li>
  <li><strong>Decimal to percentage:</strong> Multiply by 100. 0.68 x 100 = 68%.</li>
  <li><strong>Percentage to decimal:</strong> Divide by 100. 72% = 0.72.</li>
</ul>

<h4>Percentage Increase and Decrease</h4>
<p>The formula for <strong>percentage change</strong> is: Percentage Change = (Change divided by Original Value) x 100.</p>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Percentage increase:</strong> (New Value - Original Value) divided by Original Value, multiplied by 100.</li>
  <li><strong>Percentage decrease:</strong> (Original Value - New Value) divided by Original Value, multiplied by 100.</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Example:</strong> A book's price increased from GHS 40 to GHS 52. Percentage increase = (52-40)/40 x 100 = 12/40 x 100 = 30%.</p>

<h4>Finding a Percentage of a Quantity</h4>
<p>To find a percentage of a quantity, convert the percentage to a decimal or fraction and multiply.</p>
<ul>
  <li>Find 35% of GHS 200: 35/100 x 200 = GHS 70.</li>
  <li>Find 12.5% of 480 kg: 12.5/100 x 480 = 60 kg.</li>
</ul>

<h4>Reverse Percentage (Finding the Original Value)</h4>
<p>When you are given a value <strong>after</strong> a percentage change and asked to find the original, use the reverse percentage method. The percentage after the change represents the new value.</p>
<ul>
  <li><strong>After an increase:</strong> If something increased by 20%, the new value is 120% of the original. Divide new value by 1.20.</li>
  <li><strong>After a decrease:</strong> If something decreased by 15%, the new value is 85% of the original. Divide new value by 0.85.</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Example:</strong> After a 25% increase, a salary is GHS 1,250. Find the original salary. Original = 1250 divided by 1.25 = GHS 1,000.</p>
<p><strong>Example:</strong> A coat costs GHS 340 after a 15% discount. Original price = 340 divided by 0.85 = GHS 400.</p>

<h4>Profit and Loss Percentages</h4>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Profit</strong> = Selling Price - Cost Price (when Selling Price is greater than Cost Price).</li>
  <li><strong>Loss</strong> = Cost Price - Selling Price (when Cost Price is greater than Selling Price).</li>
  <li><strong>Percentage Profit</strong> = (Profit divided by Cost Price) x 100.</li>
  <li><strong>Percentage Loss</strong> = (Loss divided by Cost Price) x 100.</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Example:</strong> A trader buys an item for GHS 80 and sells it for GHS 100. Profit = GHS 20. Percentage profit = 20/80 x 100 = 25%.</p>
<p><strong>Example:</strong> A phone bought for GHS 500 is sold for GHS 425. Loss = GHS 75. Percentage loss = 75/500 x 100 = 15%.</p>

<h4>WASSCE Word Problem Strategies</h4>
<p>In WASSCE, fraction and percentage questions are often embedded in real-life contexts. Follow these steps:</p>
<ul>
  <li>Identify what is the <strong>original (whole) value</strong> and what is the <strong>part</strong>.</li>
  <li>Determine whether the question asks for a percentage OF a quantity, or what percentage one quantity IS of another.</li>
  <li>For reverse percentage, remember that the changed value is the percentage (not 100%) of the original.</li>
  <li>Always state your answer with the correct units and show working clearly for method marks.</li>
</ul>`,
