        lessonNotes: `<h4>Geometry and Mensuration</h4>
<p>Geometry deals with the properties and relationships of shapes and angles, while mensuration is the calculation of lengths, areas and volumes. Together, these topics regularly account for a significant portion of marks in WASSCE Mathematics.</p>

<h4>Angles and Their Properties</h4>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Acute angle:</strong> Between 0 and 90 degrees.</li>
  <li><strong>Right angle:</strong> Exactly 90 degrees.</li>
  <li><strong>Obtuse angle:</strong> Between 90 and 180 degrees.</li>
  <li><strong>Reflex angle:</strong> Between 180 and 360 degrees.</li>
  <li><strong>Complementary angles:</strong> Two angles that add up to 90 degrees.</li>
  <li><strong>Supplementary angles:</strong> Two angles that add up to 180 degrees.</li>
  <li><strong>Vertically opposite angles:</strong> Formed when two lines intersect; they are equal.</li>
  <li><strong>Angles on a straight line:</strong> Sum to 180 degrees.</li>
  <li><strong>Angles at a point:</strong> Sum to 360 degrees.</li>
  <li><strong>Angles in a triangle:</strong> Sum to 180 degrees.</li>
</ul>

<h4>Properties of Triangles</h4>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Equilateral triangle:</strong> All three sides equal; all angles are 60 degrees.</li>
  <li><strong>Isosceles triangle:</strong> Two sides equal; the base angles (angles opposite the equal sides) are equal.</li>
  <li><strong>Scalene triangle:</strong> All three sides different lengths; all angles different.</li>
  <li><strong>Right-angled triangle:</strong> One angle is exactly 90 degrees. The side opposite the right angle is the <strong>hypotenuse</strong>, which is always the longest side.</li>
</ul>

<h4>Circle Theorems</h4>
<p>Circle theorems are rules governing angles formed inside and around a circle. These are common in WASSCE past questions.</p>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Angle at the centre:</strong> The angle subtended at the centre is twice the angle subtended at any point on the circumference by the same arc.</li>
  <li><strong>Angles in the same segment:</strong> All angles subtended by the same chord in the same segment are equal.</li>
  <li><strong>Angle in a semicircle:</strong> Any angle inscribed in a semicircle (angle in a half-circle) is always 90 degrees. This is also called Thales' theorem.</li>
  <li><strong>Opposite angles in a cyclic quadrilateral:</strong> Add up to 180 degrees (they are supplementary).</li>
  <li><strong>Tangent to a circle:</strong> The radius drawn to a tangent point is perpendicular to the tangent (90 degrees).</li>
</ul>

<h4>Perimeter and Area Formulas</h4>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Triangle:</strong> Area = 1/2 x base x height. Perimeter = sum of all three sides.</li>
  <li><strong>Rectangle:</strong> Area = length x width. Perimeter = 2(length + width).</li>
  <li><strong>Square:</strong> Area = side squared. Perimeter = 4 x side.</li>
  <li><strong>Parallelogram:</strong> Area = base x height.</li>
  <li><strong>Trapezium:</strong> Area = 1/2 x (sum of parallel sides) x height.</li>
  <li><strong>Circle:</strong> Area = pi x r squared. Circumference = 2 x pi x r. Use pi = 22/7 or 3.142 as directed by the question.</li>
</ul>

<h4>Volume Formulas</h4>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Cuboid:</strong> Volume = length x width x height.</li>
  <li><strong>Cylinder:</strong> Volume = pi x r squared x height. Curved surface area = 2 x pi x r x h. Total surface area = 2 x pi x r x (r + h).</li>
  <li><strong>Cone:</strong> Volume = 1/3 x pi x r squared x height. Slant height l = square root of (r squared + h squared). Curved surface area = pi x r x l.</li>
  <li><strong>Sphere:</strong> Volume = 4/3 x pi x r cubed. Surface area = 4 x pi x r squared.</li>
  <li><strong>Pyramid:</strong> Volume = 1/3 x base area x height.</li>
</ul>

<h4>Pythagoras Theorem</h4>
<p>In a right-angled triangle, the square of the <strong>hypotenuse</strong> equals the sum of the squares of the other two sides.</p>
<p>Hypotenuse squared = side a squared + side b squared.</p>
<ul>
  <li>Example: A triangle has sides 6 cm and 8 cm with a right angle between them. Hypotenuse = square root of (36 + 64) = square root of 100 = 10 cm.</li>
  <li>Common Pythagorean triples to memorise: (3, 4, 5), (5, 12, 13), (8, 15, 17), (7, 24, 25).</li>
</ul>

<h4>Trigonometry: SOH-CAH-TOA</h4>
<p>Trigonometric ratios apply to <strong>right-angled triangles</strong>. Label the sides relative to the angle being used: <strong>Opposite</strong> (side facing the angle), <strong>Adjacent</strong> (side next to the angle), and <strong>Hypotenuse</strong> (longest side).</p>
<ul>
  <li><strong>SOH:</strong> Sine of angle = Opposite divided by Hypotenuse.</li>
  <li><strong>CAH:</strong> Cosine of angle = Adjacent divided by Hypotenuse.</li>
  <li><strong>TOA:</strong> Tangent of angle = Opposite divided by Adjacent.</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Sine Rule</strong> (for any triangle): a/sin A = b/sin B = c/sin C. Use when you know two angles and one side, or two sides and an angle opposite one of them.</p>
<p><strong>Cosine Rule</strong> (for any triangle): a squared = b squared + c squared - 2bc cos A. Use when you know two sides and the included angle, or all three sides.</p>`,
