        icon: '🧬',
        lessonNotes: `<h4>Genetics and Evolution: Heredity and Change Over Time</h4>
<p>Genetics is the study of how traits are inherited from parents to offspring. Evolution explains how species change over generations. Both topics are heavily tested in WASSCE Biology and require a clear understanding of key terms and processes.</p>

<h4>DNA Structure</h4>
<p>DNA (<strong>Deoxyribonucleic Acid</strong>) is the molecule that carries genetic information. Its structure is a <strong>double helix</strong> — two strands twisted around each other, discovered by Watson and Crick in 1953.</p>
<ul>
<li>Each strand is made of <strong>nucleotides</strong>, each containing a sugar (deoxyribose), a phosphate group, and a nitrogenous base.</li>
<li>The four bases are: <strong>Adenine (A), Thymine (T), Guanine (G), and Cytosine (C).</strong></li>
<li>Base pairing rules: <strong>A pairs with T</strong> (two hydrogen bonds); <strong>G pairs with C</strong> (three hydrogen bonds). These are complementary base pairs.</li>
<li>A <strong>gene</strong> is a specific sequence of DNA bases that codes for a particular protein.</li>
<li><strong>Chromosomes</strong> are long strands of DNA wound around proteins (histones). Humans have 46 chromosomes (23 pairs). <strong>Alleles</strong> are alternative forms of a gene found at the same locus on homologous chromosomes.</li>
</ul>

<h4>Mendel's Laws of Inheritance</h4>
<p>Gregor Mendel, working with pea plants in the 1860s, established the foundational laws of heredity:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Law of Segregation:</strong> Each individual has two alleles for each trait. These alleles separate during gamete formation so that each gamete carries only one allele.</li>
<li><strong>Law of Independent Assortment:</strong> Alleles for different traits are distributed to gametes independently of one another (applies to genes on different chromosomes).</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Dominant alleles</strong> are expressed in both homozygous (AA) and heterozygous (Aa) conditions. <strong>Recessive alleles</strong> are only expressed in the homozygous recessive (aa) condition.</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Genotype</strong> is the genetic makeup of an organism (e.g., Aa, BB, tt).</li>
<li><strong>Phenotype</strong> is the observable physical expression of the genotype (e.g., tall, short, round seeds).</li>
</ul>

<h4>Monohybrid and Dihybrid Crosses</h4>
<p>A <strong>monohybrid cross</strong> involves one pair of contrasting traits. Example: Tall (T) is dominant over short (t). Cross between two heterozygous tall plants (Tt x Tt):</p>
<ul>
<li>Using a Punnett square, the offspring ratio is <strong>3 tall : 1 short</strong> (genotype ratio TT : 2Tt : tt).</li>
</ul>
<p>A <strong>dihybrid cross</strong> involves two pairs of traits simultaneously. Example: Tall round (TTRR) x short wrinkled (ttrr). The F2 generation gives a <strong>9:3:3:1 phenotypic ratio</strong>.</p>

<h4>Codominance and Blood Groups</h4>
<p><strong>Codominance</strong> occurs when both alleles in a heterozygote are expressed simultaneously. The ABO blood group system is a classic example:</p>
<ul>
<li>Allele I^A produces antigen A; allele I^B produces antigen B; allele i produces no antigen.</li>
<li>Blood group A: I^A I^A or I^A i; Blood group B: I^B I^B or I^B i; Blood group AB: I^A I^B (both alleles expressed — codominance); Blood group O: ii.</li>
<li>Blood group compatibility is important for transfusions: group O is the universal donor; group AB is the universal recipient.</li>
</ul>

<h4>Sex Determination and Sex-Linked Traits</h4>
<ul>
<li>Sex is determined by sex chromosomes: females are <strong>XX</strong>, males are <strong>XY</strong>.</li>
<li>All eggs carry an X chromosome; sperm carry either X or Y. It is therefore the father who determines the sex of the offspring.</li>
<li><strong>Sex-linked traits</strong> are controlled by genes located on the X chromosome. Because males have only one X chromosome, they are more likely to express recessive sex-linked traits. Examples include red-green colour blindness and haemophilia.</li>
</ul>

<h4>Mutation</h4>
<p>A <strong>mutation</strong> is a change in the DNA sequence. Mutations can be:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Gene mutations:</strong> Changes in the base sequence of a single gene (e.g., substitution, insertion, deletion of bases). Example: sickle cell anaemia is caused by a single base substitution.</li>
<li><strong>Chromosomal mutations:</strong> Changes in chromosome number or structure. Example: Down syndrome (trisomy 21) results from an extra chromosome 21.</li>
<li>Causes of mutation include: radiation (UV light, X-rays), chemical mutagens, and errors during DNA replication.</li>
</ul>

<h4>Evolution and Natural Selection</h4>
<p><strong>Evolution</strong> is the gradual change in the inherited characteristics of populations over successive generations. Charles Darwin proposed the theory of <strong>natural selection</strong> as the mechanism:</p>
<ul>
<li>Organisms produce more offspring than can survive (overproduction).</li>
<li>There is variation among individuals in a population.</li>
<li>Some variations are heritable (passed from parent to offspring).</li>
<li>Individuals with favourable variations (adaptations) are more likely to survive and reproduce — this is called <strong>survival of the fittest</strong>.</li>
<li>Over time, favourable traits become more common in the population.</li>
</ul>

<h4>Evidence for Evolution and Speciation</h4>
<ul>
<li><strong>Fossil record:</strong> Fossils show gradual changes in organisms over time, providing direct evidence of evolution.</li>
<li><strong>Homologous structures:</strong> Similar bone structures in different species (e.g., the pentadactyl limb in humans, bats, whales) suggest a common ancestor.</li>
<li><strong>Comparative embryology:</strong> Embryos of different species look similar in early stages.</li>
<li><strong>Speciation</strong> is the formation of new species. It typically occurs through <strong>geographic isolation</strong> (allopatric speciation), where populations become separated and evolve independently until they can no longer interbreed.</li>
</ul>`,
