        name: 'Ecology & the Environment',
        icon: '🌿',
        lessonNotes: `<h4>Ecology and the Environment: Interactions in Nature</h4>
<p>Ecology is the study of how living organisms interact with each other and with their non-living environment. WASSCE questions on this topic often focus on food chains, nutrient cycles, ecological pyramids, and environmental issues.</p>

<h4>Components of an Ecosystem</h4>
<p>An <strong>ecosystem</strong> is a community of living organisms interacting with their physical environment as a system. It has two main components:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Biotic components</strong> (living): Producers (autotrophs — plants and algae that photosynthesise), consumers (heterotrophs that feed on other organisms), and decomposers (bacteria and fungi that break down dead organic matter).</li>
<li><strong>Abiotic components</strong> (non-living): Temperature, water availability, light intensity, soil type, pH, humidity, wind speed. These factors determine what organisms can survive in an environment.</li>
</ul>

<h4>Food Chains and Food Webs</h4>
<p>A <strong>food chain</strong> shows the flow of energy from one organism to the next through feeding relationships. The sequence follows: <strong>Producer → Primary Consumer → Secondary Consumer → Tertiary Consumer.</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>Example: Grass → Grasshopper → Frog → Snake → Eagle.</li>
<li>Arrows in a food chain represent the direction of energy flow (from prey to predator).</li>
<li>A <strong>food web</strong> is a network of interconnected food chains in an ecosystem. It shows the complex feeding relationships more realistically than a single food chain.</li>
</ul>

<h4>Energy Flow: The 10% Rule</h4>
<p>Energy is lost at each trophic level. On average, only about <strong>10% of the energy</strong> at one trophic level is transferred to the next. The remaining 90% is lost as heat (through respiration), used for movement, or remains in undigested material. This is why food chains rarely have more than four or five trophic levels — too little energy remains beyond that point.</p>

<h4>Ecological Pyramids</h4>
<ul>
<li><strong>Pyramid of numbers:</strong> Shows the number of organisms at each trophic level. Can be inverted (e.g., one oak tree supports many insects).</li>
<li><strong>Pyramid of biomass:</strong> Shows the total dry mass of organisms at each trophic level. Usually a true pyramid shape.</li>
<li><strong>Pyramid of energy:</strong> Shows the amount of energy at each trophic level. Always a true pyramid — energy is always lost going up the chain.</li>
</ul>

<h4>Nutrient Cycles</h4>
<p>Nutrients are recycled through the environment in biogeochemical cycles.</p>
<p>The <strong>Nitrogen Cycle</strong>:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Nitrogen fixation:</strong> Nitrogen gas (N2) from the atmosphere is converted into ammonia (NH3) by nitrogen-fixing bacteria (e.g., Rhizobium in root nodules of legumes) or by lightning.</li>
<li><strong>Nitrification:</strong> Ammonia is converted to nitrites and then nitrates by nitrifying bacteria (e.g., Nitrosomonas, Nitrobacter). Plants absorb nitrates through their roots.</li>
<li><strong>Denitrification:</strong> Denitrifying bacteria convert nitrates back into nitrogen gas, releasing it into the atmosphere.</li>
<li><strong>Decomposition:</strong> Decomposers break down dead organic matter, releasing ammonia (ammonification).</li>
</ul>
<p>The <strong>Carbon Cycle</strong>:</p>
<ul>
<li>Carbon is removed from the atmosphere by <strong>photosynthesis</strong> (plants absorb CO2).</li>
<li>Carbon is returned to the atmosphere by <strong>respiration</strong> (all living things), <strong>decomposition</strong>, and <strong>combustion</strong> (burning fossil fuels and wood).</li>
<li>The burning of fossil fuels has significantly increased atmospheric CO2, contributing to the <strong>greenhouse effect</strong> and global warming.</li>
</ul>

<h4>Population Ecology</h4>
<p>A <strong>population</strong> is a group of individuals of the same species living in the same area. Population size is determined by:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Natality (birth rate):</strong> Increases population size.</li>
<li><strong>Mortality (death rate):</strong> Decreases population size.</li>
<li><strong>Immigration:</strong> Individuals moving into a population — increases size.</li>
<li><strong>Emigration:</strong> Individuals moving out — decreases size.</li>
<li><strong>Carrying capacity:</strong> The maximum population size that an environment can sustainably support, given available resources. When a population exceeds carrying capacity, it declines due to limited food, space, and disease.</li>
</ul>

<h4>Ecological Relationships and Succession</h4>
<ul>
<li><strong>Predator-prey relationships:</strong> As prey numbers increase, predator numbers increase; predators then reduce prey numbers, which in turn reduces predator numbers — creating a cyclical relationship.</li>
<li><strong>Primary succession:</strong> The development of an ecosystem in a previously lifeless area (e.g., bare rock). Pioneer species (e.g., lichens) colonise first, gradually building soil for more complex communities.</li>
<li><strong>Secondary succession:</strong> Recovery of an ecosystem after a disturbance (e.g., forest fire). Soil remains, so recovery is faster than primary succession.</li>
</ul>

<h4>Environmental Issues</h4>
<ul>
<li><strong>Deforestation:</strong> Removal of forests for agriculture and logging leads to loss of biodiversity, soil erosion, disruption of the water cycle, and increased atmospheric CO2.</li>
<li><strong>Pollution:</strong> Contamination of air (CO2, SO2), water (fertilisers causing eutrophication), and soil (pesticides) disrupts ecosystems and threatens human health.</li>
<li><strong>Desertification:</strong> Degradation of land in arid regions due to overgrazing, deforestation, and poor farming practices.</li>
<li><strong>Conservation:</strong> Efforts to protect species and habitats include national parks, game reserves, captive breeding programmes, and sustainable resource management.</li>
</ul>`,
