        lessonNotes: `<h4>Human Physiology: Body Systems and Their Functions</h4>
<p>Human physiology covers the functioning of the major organ systems of the body. WASSCE questions frequently test knowledge of digestive enzymes, the heart, blood, gas exchange, the nervous system, and excretion. Mastering the details of each system is key to scoring well.</p>

<h4>The Digestive System</h4>
<p>The digestive system breaks down food into small molecules that can be absorbed into the blood. Key organs and their functions:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Mouth:</strong> Mechanical digestion by teeth; salivary glands produce <strong>amylase</strong> which begins the digestion of starch into maltose.</li>
<li><strong>Stomach:</strong> Produces gastric juice containing <strong>pepsin</strong> (digests proteins into polypeptides) and hydrochloric acid (kills bacteria, provides acidic pH for pepsin).</li>
<li><strong>Small intestine:</strong> Main site of digestion and absorption. Pancreatic juice contains amylase, <strong>lipase</strong> (digests fats into fatty acids and glycerol), and protease. Bile (produced by the liver, stored in the gall bladder) emulsifies fats. Nutrients are absorbed through villi and microvilli into the blood and lymph.</li>
<li><strong>Large intestine:</strong> Absorbs water; the remaining material forms faeces.</li>
</ul>

<h4>Nutrition</h4>
<ul>
<li><strong>Carbohydrates:</strong> Main energy source. Include sugars (glucose, fructose) and starch. Found in rice, yam, cassava, bread.</li>
<li><strong>Proteins:</strong> For growth and repair. Made of amino acids. Found in meat, fish, eggs, beans.</li>
<li><strong>Fats:</strong> Energy store, insulation, hormone production. Found in oils, butter, nuts.</li>
<li><strong>Vitamins:</strong> Required in small amounts for specific functions. Vitamin C (scurvy prevention), Vitamin D (bone development), Vitamin A (vision).</li>
<li><strong>Minerals:</strong> Calcium (bones and teeth), iron (haemoglobin), iodine (thyroid hormone).</li>
</ul>

<h4>The Circulatory System</h4>
<p>The heart has <strong>four chambers</strong>: right atrium, right ventricle, left atrium, left ventricle. The left side pumps oxygenated blood; the right side pumps deoxygenated blood.</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Pulmonary circulation:</strong> Right ventricle → pulmonary artery → lungs (gas exchange) → pulmonary veins → left atrium.</li>
<li><strong>Systemic circulation:</strong> Left ventricle → aorta → body tissues → vena cava → right atrium.</li>
<li><strong>Blood components:</strong> Red blood cells (carry oxygen via haemoglobin); White blood cells (immune defence); Platelets (blood clotting); Plasma (liquid that carries dissolved substances including hormones, nutrients, and waste).</li>
<li>Blood group compatibility must be considered in transfusions. Incompatible blood can cause agglutination (clumping), which is life-threatening.</li>
</ul>

<h4>The Respiratory System</h4>
<ul>
<li>Breathing involves the diaphragm and intercostal muscles. During inhalation, the diaphragm contracts and flattens, the ribcage moves up and out, increasing thoracic volume and decreasing pressure, drawing air in.</li>
<li><strong>Gas exchange</strong> occurs in the <strong>alveoli</strong>: oxygen diffuses from air in the alveolus into the blood capillaries; carbon dioxide diffuses in the opposite direction. Alveoli are adapted with thin walls, moist surfaces, and a rich blood supply.</li>
</ul>

<h4>The Nervous System</h4>
<p>The nervous system coordinates responses to stimuli.</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Central Nervous System (CNS):</strong> Brain (control centre) and spinal cord (conducts impulses and controls reflex actions).</li>
<li><strong>Peripheral Nervous System:</strong> Nerves connecting the CNS to the rest of the body.</li>
<li><strong>Neurones:</strong> Sensory neurones carry impulses from receptors to the CNS. Motor neurones carry impulses from the CNS to effectors. Relay (interneurons) connect sensory and motor neurones in the spinal cord.</li>
<li>A <strong>reflex arc</strong> is an automatic, rapid response to a stimulus: stimulus → receptor → sensory neurone → relay neurone → motor neurone → effector → response. The reflex arc bypasses conscious thought in the brain.</li>
</ul>

<h4>The Endocrine System</h4>
<ul>
<li><strong>Pancreas:</strong> Secretes <strong>insulin</strong> (lowers blood glucose) and <strong>glucagon</strong> (raises blood glucose). Diabetes results from insulin deficiency or resistance.</li>
<li><strong>Adrenal glands:</strong> Secrete <strong>adrenaline</strong> (prepares body for fight-or-flight: increased heart rate, dilated pupils).</li>
<li><strong>Sex hormones:</strong> Oestrogen and progesterone (females), testosterone (males) — control secondary sexual characteristics and reproductive cycles.</li>
</ul>

<h4>Excretion: Kidneys and Skin</h4>
<p>Excretion is the removal of metabolic waste products from the body.</p>
<ul>
<li>The <strong>kidneys</strong> produce urine through three processes: <strong>ultrafiltration</strong> (blood is filtered under pressure in the glomerulus — glucose, urea, water, and salts pass into the Bowman's capsule); <strong>selective reabsorption</strong> (glucose, most water, and useful salts are reabsorbed back into the blood); and <strong>urine formation</strong> (urea, excess salts, and water remain as urine, passed to the bladder via the ureter).</li>
<li>The <strong>skin</strong> excretes water and small amounts of salts and urea through sweat. Sweating also helps regulate body temperature.</li>
</ul>`,
