        icon: '⚛️',
        lessonNotes: `<h4>Atomic Structure: Building Blocks of Matter</h4>
<p>Atomic structure is the foundation of all chemistry. Understanding how atoms are constructed, how electrons are arranged, and how the periodic table is organised is essential for success in WASSCE Chemistry. Many questions in bonding, reactions, and periodicity all link back to this topic.</p>

<h4>Historical Models of the Atom</h4>
<ul>
<li><strong>Dalton's model (1803):</strong> Atoms are tiny, indivisible spheres. Each element has atoms of a specific mass. This model could not explain the existence of subatomic particles.</li>
<li><strong>Thomson's model (1897) — Plum Pudding Model:</strong> After discovering the electron, Thomson proposed that atoms consist of a positive sphere of charge with electrons embedded in it like plums in a pudding.</li>
<li><strong>Rutherford's model (1911) — Nuclear Model:</strong> Based on the gold foil experiment, in which alpha particles were fired at gold foil. Most passed through, but some were deflected at large angles. This showed that atoms have a tiny, dense, positively charged <strong>nucleus</strong> with electrons surrounding it in mostly empty space.</li>
<li><strong>Bohr's model (1913):</strong> Electrons orbit the nucleus in fixed <strong>energy levels (shells)</strong>. Electrons in higher shells have more energy. When electrons absorb energy they move to higher shells; when they release energy they drop to lower shells, emitting light.</li>
</ul>

<h4>Subatomic Particles</h4>
<ul>
<li><strong>Protons:</strong> Positively charged (+1), found in the nucleus. Mass of 1 atomic mass unit (amu).</li>
<li><strong>Neutrons:</strong> No charge (0), found in the nucleus. Mass of 1 amu.</li>
<li><strong>Electrons:</strong> Negatively charged (-1), found in shells around the nucleus. Mass approximately 1/1840 amu — negligible.</li>
<li>In a neutral atom, the number of protons equals the number of electrons.</li>
</ul>

<h4>Atomic Number, Mass Number, and Isotopes</h4>
<ul>
<li><strong>Atomic number (Z):</strong> The number of protons in the nucleus. It uniquely identifies an element. Equal to the number of electrons in a neutral atom.</li>
<li><strong>Mass number (A):</strong> Total number of protons and neutrons in the nucleus. Number of neutrons = Mass number − Atomic number.</li>
<li><strong>Isotopes:</strong> Atoms of the same element with the same atomic number but different mass numbers (different numbers of neutrons). Example: Carbon-12 and Carbon-14 are both carbon (6 protons) but have 6 and 8 neutrons respectively. Isotopes have the same chemical properties but different physical properties. Radioactive isotopes are used in medicine (cancer treatment) and carbon dating.</li>
</ul>

<h4>Electronic Configuration</h4>
<p>Electrons are arranged in shells (energy levels) around the nucleus. The shells fill in order: the first shell holds a maximum of <strong>2 electrons</strong>; the second holds <strong>8</strong>; the third holds <strong>8</strong> (at WASSCE level). This is written as a series of numbers.</p>
<ul>
<li>Sodium (Na, atomic number 11): configuration 2, 8, 1 — one electron in the outer shell.</li>
<li>Chlorine (Cl, atomic number 17): configuration 2, 8, 7 — seven electrons in the outer shell.</li>
<li>The number of electrons in the outer shell (valence electrons) determines chemical behaviour.</li>
<li><strong>Electron dot diagrams</strong> (Lewis structures) show the arrangement of valence electrons around the symbol of an element using dots.</li>
</ul>

<h4>The Periodic Table: Periods and Groups</h4>
<ul>
<li><strong>Periods</strong> are horizontal rows. Moving across a period, the atomic number increases by one. Elements in the same period have the same number of electron shells.</li>
<li><strong>Groups</strong> are vertical columns. Elements in the same group have the same number of valence electrons and therefore similar chemical properties.</li>
<li><strong>Group 1 (Alkali metals):</strong> 1 valence electron; highly reactive; react vigorously with water to produce hydrogen gas and an alkaline solution.</li>
<li><strong>Group 2 (Alkaline earth metals):</strong> 2 valence electrons; less reactive than Group 1.</li>
<li><strong>Group 7 (Halogens):</strong> 7 valence electrons; form diatomic molecules; highly reactive non-metals that gain one electron to form halide ions.</li>
<li><strong>Group 0 (Noble gases):</strong> Full outer shells; chemically inert (unreactive); used in lighting (neon, argon).</li>
</ul>

<h4>Periodic Trends</h4>
<ul>
<li><strong>Atomic radius:</strong> Decreases across a period (increasing nuclear charge pulls electrons closer); increases down a group (more electron shells added).</li>
<li><strong>Ionisation energy:</strong> The energy required to remove an electron from an atom. Increases across a period; decreases down a group.</li>
<li><strong>Electronegativity:</strong> The ability of an atom to attract electrons in a bond. Increases across a period; decreases down a group. Fluorine is the most electronegative element.</li>
<li><strong>Metals</strong> are found on the left and centre of the periodic table; <strong>non-metals</strong> on the right; <strong>metalloids</strong> (e.g., silicon, germanium) lie along the dividing line and show properties of both.</li>
</ul>`,
