        icon: '⛽',
        lessonNotes: `<h4>Organic Chemistry: Carbon Compounds and Their Reactions</h4>
<p>Organic chemistry is the study of carbon-containing compounds. Carbon is a unique element — it is <strong>tetravalent</strong> (forms four covalent bonds) and can bond to itself, forming long chains, branches, and rings. This gives rise to an enormous variety of compounds. WASSCE questions on this topic cover naming, functional groups, reactions, and polymers.</p>

<h4>Hydrocarbons</h4>
<p>Hydrocarbons contain only carbon and hydrogen atoms. The three main families are:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Alkanes</strong> (general formula CnH2n+2): contain only single C-C bonds — <strong>saturated</strong>. Example: methane (CH4), ethane (C2H6), propane (C3H8). They are relatively unreactive due to strong C-C and C-H bonds.</li>
<li><strong>Alkenes</strong> (general formula CnH2n): contain at least one C=C double bond — <strong>unsaturated</strong>. Example: ethene (C2H4), propene (C3H6). More reactive than alkanes due to the double bond. They decolourise bromine water (an important test for unsaturation).</li>
<li><strong>Alkynes</strong> (general formula CnH2n-2): contain at least one C≡C triple bond. Example: ethyne (C2H2). Very reactive.</li>
</ul>

<h4>IUPAC Naming</h4>
<p>The International Union of Pure and Applied Chemistry (IUPAC) system uses prefixes to indicate the number of carbon atoms in the longest chain:</p>
<ul>
<li>1 carbon: <strong>meth-</strong></li>
<li>2 carbons: <strong>eth-</strong></li>
<li>3 carbons: <strong>prop-</strong></li>
<li>4 carbons: <strong>but-</strong></li>
<li>5 carbons: <strong>pent-</strong></li>
<li>Suffixes: -ane (alkanes), -ene (alkenes), -yne (alkynes), -ol (alcohols), -al (aldehydes), -one (ketones), -anoic acid (carboxylic acids).</li>
</ul>

<h4>Functional Groups</h4>
<p>A <strong>functional group</strong> is an atom or group of atoms that gives an organic molecule its characteristic chemical properties:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Alcohol (-OH):</strong> e.g., ethanol (C2H5OH). Used as a solvent and fuel. Produced by fermentation.</li>
<li><strong>Aldehyde (-CHO):</strong> e.g., methanal (HCHO). Reducing agent; reduces Fehling's solution and Tollens' reagent.</li>
<li><strong>Ketone (C=O):</strong> e.g., propanone (CH3COCH3). Does not reduce Fehling's solution (distinguishes ketones from aldehydes).</li>
<li><strong>Carboxylic acid (-COOH):</strong> e.g., ethanoic acid (CH3COOH). Weak acid; reacts with alcohols to form esters.</li>
<li><strong>Ester (-COO-):</strong> Formed from a carboxylic acid and an alcohol. Has characteristic fruity smells; used in perfumes and flavourings.</li>
<li><strong>Amine (-NH2):</strong> e.g., methylamine (CH3NH2). Acts as a base; important in amino acids.</li>
</ul>

<h4>Reactions of Organic Compounds</h4>
<ul>
<li><strong>Substitution reactions (alkanes):</strong> Alkanes react with halogens in the presence of UV light. A hydrogen atom is replaced by a halogen. e.g., CH4 + Cl2 → CH3Cl + HCl (chlorination of methane). This is a <strong>free radical</strong> mechanism.</li>
<li><strong>Addition reactions (alkenes):</strong> The double bond breaks, and atoms are added across it. e.g., CH2=CH2 + H2 → CH3-CH3 (hydrogenation — used to harden vegetable oils). Also: CH2=CH2 + Br2 → CH2BrCH2Br (addition of bromine — decolourises bromine water).</li>
<li><strong>Combustion:</strong> All hydrocarbons burn in oxygen to produce CO2 and H2O (complete combustion). Incomplete combustion produces CO (carbon monoxide) and soot (C).</li>
<li><strong>Esterification:</strong> Carboxylic acid + alcohol → ester + water (in the presence of a concentrated H2SO4 catalyst).</li>
</ul>

<h4>Polymers</h4>
<p>Polymers are very large molecules made by joining many small molecules (<strong>monomers</strong>) together.</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Addition polymerisation:</strong> Unsaturated monomers (alkenes) join together by breaking the double bond. No by-product is formed. Example: ethene (CH2=CH2) polymerises to form <strong>polyethene</strong> (-CH2-CH2-)n. Also: propene → polypropene; chloroethene → PVC.</li>
<li><strong>Condensation polymerisation:</strong> Monomers join together with the elimination of a small molecule (usually water). Example: <strong>nylon</strong> (a polyamide) is formed from a diamine and a dicarboxylic acid; <strong>polyester</strong> (e.g., Terylene) is formed from a diol and a dicarboxylic acid.</li>
</ul>

<h4>Fermentation</h4>
<p><strong>Fermentation</strong> is the anaerobic breakdown of glucose by yeast (enzymes) to produce ethanol and carbon dioxide:</p>
<p><strong>C6H12O6 → 2C2H5OH + 2CO2</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>Conditions: yeast (contains the enzyme zymase), warm temperature (about 30-40°C), absence of oxygen, slightly acidic conditions.</li>
<li>The alcohol content increases until it reaches about 14-15%, at which point the yeast is killed by the ethanol. Distillation is used to increase the alcohol concentration further.</li>
<li>Industrial applications: production of alcoholic beverages (beer, wine, spirits) and bioethanol fuel.</li>
</ul>`,
